of sympathetic nerves to colon","Contraction of circular smooth muscle in rectum","Contraction of internal anal sphincter","Relaxation of external anal sphincter and puborectalis muscles"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVoluntary control of defaecation primarily involves \u003Cstrong\u003Erelaxation of the external anal sphincter and puborectalis muscles\u003C/strong\u003E. These skeletal muscles are under conscious control via somatic nerves. When appropriate social circumstances exist, voluntary relaxation of these muscles allows defaecation to proceed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContraction of internal anal sphincter\u003C/strong\u003E - This smooth muscle automatically relaxes in response to rectal distension via the rectoanal inhibitory reflex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of parasympathetic nerves to rectum\u003C/strong\u003E - Parasympathetic stimulation (not inhibition) enhances colonic motility and is part of the defaecation reflex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of sympathetic nerves to colon\u003C/strong\u003E - Sympathetic stimulation actually inhibits colonic motility and is not involved in initiating defaecation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContraction of circular smooth muscle in rectum\u003C/strong\u003E - While this occurs during defaecation, it is an involuntary response rather than under voluntary control\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The defaecation reflex is initiated when the rectum is distended to approximately 18 mL volume.","Voluntary control of defaecation involves coordinated relaxation of the external anal sphincter and puborectalis muscles.","The internal anal sphincter relaxes automatically in response to rectal distension via the rectoanal inhibitory reflex."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17225"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T11:57:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T11:57:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9915"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4911"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","